        "timestamp": "2018-08-17 12:04:57.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(2 comments)\n\nits increasing the code coverage for RestClientMsgs.java which was otherwise not covered earlier.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "bfbec54a85420ad54d539ebeb23e6071f84e0b13",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 703,
          "name": "Tian Lee",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "TianL@amdocs.com",
          "username": "TianL"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-17 13:17:35.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> (2 comments)\n > \n > its increasing the code coverage for RestClientMsgs.java which was\n > otherwise not covered earlier.\n\nFirstly, there are 11 Enums in that class, why are you only testing one of them?\n\nSecondly, I don't believe creating tests that have no business value other than increasing test coverage statistics is good practice.\n\nThirdly, in Eclipse, using EclEmma plugin, adding your new test made no improvement to the code coverage stats.\n\nThe Enum values in that class are all used in the generation of error messages. A much more useful test would be one that produces the error scenarios that make use of the Enums. By doing this, you will also gain coverage of the error generation code, as well as testing of the negative business use cases.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "91e7ca1aa283a1dcb2eac3096fc47ac6ceac3e22",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1313,
          "name": "Mark Leonard",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "mark.j.leonard@gmail.com",
          "username": "mark.j.leonard"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-08-17 13:37:36.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nCalling the Enum method .name() does not appear to increase the code coverage measurement. A solution that does have a measurable effect is to call .valueOf() on the Enum. For example:\n        RestClientMsgs.valueOf(RestClientMsgs.HTTP_RESPONSE.toString());\n\nThis artificial means of increasing the code coverage does not improve code quality. It would be better to write a functional test involving the Enum which contains an assertion (that could genuinely be falsifiable).",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
